obo:GO_0003674  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_3585  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: 18/5/2018 Pim\nrule: NAS_CPLX_1\nrationale: Ribosomes are present in the axonal compartment (Fig.1, RL22 used as marker protein using the RiboTag mouse line; electron and fluorescence microscopy) and protein translation is shown to occur in this compartment (PMID:27321671). RS14 is a generally accepted constituent of the ribosome. No functions of RS14 are known independent from the ribosomal complex. Inference to term \"ribosome (GO:0005840)\" part_of \"presynapse (GO:0098793)\" is trivial.\nC_ref CC: SynGO ID #1681 (\"presynaptic ribosome\")\nP_inf CC: SynGO ID #3207\nP_inf CC additional:\n- Biesemann et al.(2014), PMID:24413018, TableS1, prep:synapse\n- Bayes et al.(2012), PMID:23071613, TableS1, prep:psd\n- Takamori et al.(2006), PMID:17110340, TableS1, prep:sv\n- Distler et al.(2014), PMID:25211037, Table S1, prep:synapse\n- Fernandez et al.(2009), PMID:19455133, TableS1, prep:psd\nComplex membership: RS14 protein is a fixed member of the 40S ribosomal subunit complex.\n- Shown in crystal structure (PMID:28138070, see Fig.1, name: us11)\n- GO annotations to \"structural constituent of ribosome (GO:0003735)\" (ISO and IEA). Experimental description: \"In-depth protein profiling of the postsynaptic density from mouse hippocampus using data-independent acquisition proteomics.\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9681-3318" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0269-0311" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9377-7414" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9880-1214" ;
        dc:date           "2018-05-28" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_3585" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

